.portfolio-item__section.container--first
  .container.container--page-width.container--content
    %h3.heading--section.portfolio-item__section-name
      Discovery & Background
    %p
      We’ve heard feedback—from customers, attendees, and internal employees alike—that our messaging features are hard to use, and that attendees don’t always know when someone’s trying to get in touch with them. We knew it was time for a change; but there were several potential problems to dig into we needed to scope them down to the most important ones.
    %p
      My product manager and I kicked off the project with some discovery and brainstorming sessions with internal stakeholders in different departments of the company. We started by creating empathy maps for several different user types who are typically at an event: Novice Attendee, Expert Attendee, Exhibitor, and Event Planner. Many of our team members are remote, so we used a tool called Realtime Board to capture everyone’s ideas. We left this exercise pretty open ended, as we wanted to get everything up on the board before narrowing it down. Here’s a snippet from our Novice Attendee board:

    = image_tag "#{ item.sample_image_path }messaging-empathy-map.png", alt: "#{ item.name }: Messaging Empathy Map", class: 'portfolio-item__image--solo'

    %p
      Next we compiled the biggest problems related to networking, messaging, and notifications that we’ve heard from our different user types. We grouped them by themes and each set our top priorities by putting dots on the themes and individual problems we thought were most important.

    = image_tag "#{ item.sample_image_path }messaging-problems.png", alt: "#{ item.name }: Messaging Problems", class: 'portfolio-item__image'

.portfolio-item__section
  .container.container--page-width.container--content
    .dd-unified-messaging__before-section
      .col-left-wrapper
        .col-left
          %h3.heading--section.portfolio-item__section-name
            The Objective
          %p
            We have several different messaging features that live in different sections of the app: Direct Messages, Topic Channels, and Session Channels. (At the time this made sense with the general schema we use, since event organizers can show and hide app sections to toggle these features on or off individually.) Topic Channels are group chatrooms based on topics that the event organizer sets up in advance, and that attendees can browse and join. Session Channels are a chatroom for every session, which you can find by going to the session in the Agenda section.
          %p
            We decided that the main issues we wanted to address were related to missing notifiations and ease of use. This was also confirmed by the metrics we were seeing around our messaging usage. The two biggest metrics we wanted to move were:

          %ol.objectives--dd-unified-messaging
            %li
              %strong Attendee adoption & engagement.
              We have very low percentages of attendees using these messaging features and really want to see this go up. We think there are a variety of reasons for this, including: attendees not knowing that the features exist to begin with; not noticing when they receive a message; and not understanding how they should use Topic Channels and Session Channels.
            %li
              %strong Event organizer adoption.
              Many event organizers did not enable these features for their events at all. There were many reasons cited for this, but two big ones were: they didn’t know the features existed or how to use them; or they tried them at one event and didn’t see a lot of attendees using them, so it didn’t seem worth setting them up again.

      .col-right
        .caption
          Messaging features live in  3 different places
