  .container.container--page-width.container--content
    %h3.heading--section.portfolio-item__section-name
      Weighing Navigation Options
    %p
      I looked other social apps with messaging features to see what users are used to. They all seemed to handle messaging in one of few different ways: separate sectons for messaging and notifications; or a single notifications tab with Activity and Messaging notifications in subtabs. Within messaging, some apps had different subtabs for different types of messaging. I did some rough sketches of what these options would look like in our app:

    = image_tag "#{ item.sample_image_path }messaging-nav-sketches.png", alt: "#{ item.name }: Messaging Navigation Sketches", class: 'portfolio-item__image'

.portfolio-item__section
  .container.container--page-width.container--content
    %h3.heading--section.portfolio-item__section-name
      The "Final" Designs
    %p
      Before we started development, we had calls with different types of customers to walk through designs and get their reactions. For the most part they were really excited and positive, and could clearly understand what was going on in the workflow we showed them. One of things we learned was that the phrase “Topic Channels” is not very clear. Customers who had not used this feature before weren’t sure what they were for, so I adjusted the language a bit.
    %p
      We decided not to make any changes to Session Channels, and instead to focus on Direct Messages and Topic Channels for V1. We felt that DMs and Topic Channels have the clearest use case and the most potential to be improved by these changes.
    %p
      This project is currently in development. Here are the mockups that are being implemented for our first iteration.

    .dd-unified-messaging__ios-final-designs
      .col-left
        = render partial: 'portfolio_items/iphone_frame', locals: { item: item, image_filename: 'ios_messages--empty.png', desc: 'OS: Messages (Empty)' }

      .col-mid
        %p.aside--right
          Direct messages are more important than new topic chat messages, so unread DMs always appear on top. Push notifications will only be sent for direct messages, but the red dot will appear on the Messages section for everything.
        %p.aside--left
          I wanted attendees to be able to start browsing as soon as they get to the Messages tab. Horiziontal scrolling carousels allow for more recommendations to be addded later.

      .col-right
        = render partial: 'portfolio_items/iphone_frame', locals: { item: item, image_filename: 'ios_messages--unread.png', desc: 'iOS: Messages (Unread)' }

    %p
      For event organizers too, messaging features were all in different places in the CMS. I put them all in one section so they were easily discoverable, but can still be turned on and off individually. We're also planning start turning them on for all events by default&mdash;with a little tutorial letting organizers know about the changes we made.

